"""
Fill script: 2 Samuel mkt-christ ch8–11 — fills missing typological/Christological
commentary entries. Ch8: David's empire and justice (type of Messiah's universal kingdom).
Ch9: Mephibosheth (type of the sinner restored by covenant grace). Ch11: David and
Bathsheba / Uriah (David as anti-type, Christ as the true innocent sufferer and
righteous covenant-keeper). v3 in ch11 and v7/13 in ch9 and v15 in ch8 already exist.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(book, ctype):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{ctype}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(book, ctype, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{ctype}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

FILL = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>David's defeat of the Philistines and capture of Metheg-ammah marks the turning of Israel's long border war into dominion — the nation that had oppressed Israel from Samson's day is brought under tribute. This pattern of the oppressor subdued foreshadows Christ's Advent conquest: where David strikes the Philistine stronghold, the Son of David treads the serpent's head (Gen 3:15), and where David extends sovereignty, Christ's resurrection authority extends to all nations (Matt 28:18). <em>wayyiqqaḥ</em> — 'he took the bridle of the mother city' — the phrase used here (<em>metheg ha-ammāh</em>) denotes the authority-rein of a chief city, typifying that the Messiah inherits the reins of the kingdoms of the world (Rev 11:15).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The measuring of the Moabites with a cord — two lines to death, one to life — is a stark image of sovereign mercy within judgment. David, the son of a Moabite woman (Ruth), does not spare all Moab but apportions grace and judgment by royal decree. The type prefigures Christ who is both the Judge who measures (Rev 11:1; Amos 7:7-8) and the Redeemer who preserves a remnant out of all peoples. The Moabites brought under tribute evoke Ruth's inclusion in the covenant people — the line that produced David and ultimately Christ is itself of Moabite origin, a testimony to grace that crosses ethnic lines (Ruth 4:17; Matt 1:5).</p>",
    "3": "<p>David smites Hadadezer of Zobah as the king goes to restore his monument at the Euphrates River — the great covenant boundary of Abraham's grant (Gen 15:18). David presses Israel's territorial claim to the full Abrahamic boundary, an ambition never achieved in the Mosaic conquest. This typologically signals that David's kingdom is a partial, anticipatory fulfillment of the Abrahamic covenant, and that its complete realization awaits the greater David: Christ, whose inheritance is the uttermost parts of the earth (Ps 2:8). The Euphrates boundary reappears in Revelation's judgment on the sixth trumpet (Rev 9:14), marking the eschatological completion of Christ's dominion.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David hamstrings all but a hundred chariot horses — a Deuteronomic requirement for Israel's king who must not multiply horses (Deut 17:16). This act of faithful restraint distinguishes David from Solomon who would later violate it (1 Kings 10:26), and from the Egyptian chariot-power that symbolized autonomy from YHWH. The true King of Israel does not trust in chariots or horses (Ps 20:7); this verse is typologically the obverse of Christ's entry into Jerusalem on a donkey (Zech 9:9; Matt 21:5) — both acts demonstrate that the Messiah's kingdom advances by YHWH's power, not military might.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Syrians of Damascus come to help Hadadezer and David smites twenty-two thousand of them — the imperial radius of David's victories expanding northward from Philistia to Zobah to Aram. Each successive victory redraws the map of the Promised Land toward its Abrahamic bounds, and the pattern is theologically cumulative: YHWH is warrior-king advancing through David. This finds its antitype in Christ whose resurrection-victory over principalities and powers (Col 2:15) is followed by the progressive subjugation of hostile kingdoms until all things are under his feet (1 Cor 15:25; Ps 110:1-2).</p>",
    "6": "<p>David places garrisons in Syria of Damascus and all the Syrians become servants bringing tribute. The caption from the narrator — 'YHWH saved David wherever he went' — is the theological key to the entire chapter. David's empire is not the result of military genius but of divine election, and this very caption (repeated verbatim in v14) brackets the chapter as a testimony to the Lord's faithfulness to 2 Sam 7:1-16. Every victory is the advance of the covenant promise; every tributary nation points toward the day when all nations serve the Son of David (Ps 72:11; Rev 21:24).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The shields of gold taken from Hadadezer's servants are brought to Jerusalem, enriching the city with plunder from the nations. This dedication of spoil to the holy city anticipates Solomon's temple-building funded by David's wars (1 Kings 5:3; 1 Chron 22:8), and typologically evokes the eschatological vision of Revelation 21:24-26 where the kings of the earth bring their glory into the New Jerusalem. David's wars are not merely political consolidation but the gathering of tribute toward the building of God's house — a pattern fulfilled in Christ who, having disarmed the powers (Col 2:15), is now building his Church from every nation (Matt 16:18).</p>",
    "8": "<p>From Betah and Berothai, cities of Hadadezer, David takes a great amount of bronze — the same metal that will fill Solomon's temple (the bronze sea, the bronze altar, the pillars Jachin and Boaz). The temple's bronze is the transmuted spoil of conquered kingdoms, and typologically this enacts the principle that the wealth of the nations flows to the house of God (Isa 60:5; Hag 2:7). In the same way, Christ's victory gathers the gifts and honor of all peoples into the service of his Bride, the Church, making her glorious beyond Solomon's temple (Eph 5:27; John 17:22).</p>",
    "9": "<p>When Toi king of Hamath hears that David has defeated Hadadezer, he sends his son Joram with silver, gold, and bronze — tribute from a distant king who has recognized the new power. Toi's initiative without compulsion typifies the willing submission of the nations that characterizes the Messianic age: 'All kings will bow down before him, all nations will serve him' (Ps 72:11). Hamath is at the northern limit of the ideal Promised Land (Num 13:21; 2 Kings 14:25), making Toi's tribute a symbolic arrival at the covenant borders — the extent of David's empire again pressing toward the Abrahamic promise.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Joram carries articles of silver, gold, and bronze to David, who dedicates them to YHWH along with the silver and gold taken from all the nations he has subdued. The verb <em>hiqdîš</em> — 'he dedicated' — signals that empire is consecrated to covenant: David's universal conquests are not for personal wealth but for the glory of Israel's God. This theology of dedicated spoil is the OT root of Paul's teaching that the Gentile mission returns its wealth to the Jerusalem church as an offering (Rom 15:26-27) and ultimately of the New Jerusalem's receiving the glory of the nations (Rev 21:26). All of David's wars serve the temple; all of Christ's victories serve the new creation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David's dedication of the silver and gold from Edom, Moab, Ammonites, Philistines, and Amalek points to the breadth of his subjugation — a geography that encompasses all of Israel's traditional enemies, the nations that opposed the Exodus and settlement. Their surrender and their tribute dedicated to YHWH is eschatologically typological: the Psalter repeatedly projects this same gathering onto the Messianic future (Ps 68:29-31; 76:11), and Revelation 21 shows every hostile nation's wealth transformed into glory for the New Jerusalem. Christ does not merely subdue his enemies but converts their tribute into the beautification of his Bride.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The summary of dedications extends to Aram (Syria) and its kings — the northern empire-arc from Philistia to Syria. The list functions as a covenant-geography testimony: YHWH is keeping his Abraham-promise by stages. The typological weight lies in the inclusiveness of the dedicatory act — every hostile nation becomes a supplier for the house of God. In the NT this pattern is enacted when Paul collects the Gentile offering for the Jerusalem church (2 Cor 8-9) and ultimately fulfilled when the kings of the earth bring their glory into the heavenly city (Rev 21:24). The enemies of God's people are not merely defeated; they are recruited into the worship of the King.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David makes a name for himself in the Valley of Salt, defeating eighteen thousand Edomites. The 'name' (<em>šēm</em>) is the key term: making a name by conquest is the aspiration of empire from Babel onward (Gen 11:4), but David's name is made in service of YHWH's covenant. The true name-bearer is the Coming One whose 'name is above every name' (Phil 2:9) — a name not seized like Babel but received by the Father as the reward of his obedience and suffering. The Valley of Salt defeat of Edom (Esau's descendants, the perennial symbol of the flesh opposing the spirit, cf. Mal 1:2-4; Rom 9:13) foreshadows the ultimate eschatological reversal where the Edomic principle is judged (Obad 1).</p>",
    "14": "<p>David puts garrisons throughout Edom — Edom becomes a vassal state — and again the narrator summarizes: 'YHWH saved David wherever he went.' This second occurrence of the refrain (see v6) frames ch8 as a theological unity. The pattern of divine faithfulness surrounding human military activity insists that the narrative's hero is YHWH, not David. The typological claim is therefore that Christ's universal lordship is not his own achievement exercised independently but the Father's gift — 'all authority has been given to me' (Matt 28:18) — and that every extension of the kingdom is 'YHWH saving wherever he goes': the mission of the Spirit through the Church (Acts 1:8).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Joab is over the army, Jehoshaphat is recorder — the administrative list of ch8 vv16-18 situates David's military victories within covenant governance. The king who defeats nations also structures justice in Israel. Joab's role as commander is typologically freighted: he is both loyal instrument and future source of moral compromise (ch11; ch20), illustrating that no human instrument perfectly serves the perfect King. Christ needs no flawed Joab — he himself is both king and commander (Rev 19:11-16), and his administration is without the corruption that plagues David's court. The list's mundane character actually deepens the type: the greater David administers perfect governance where David's court is only an approximation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Zadok and Ahimelech are priests — the dual priesthood reflecting the tension between Zadokite and Abiatharic lines that will resolve in Solomon's reign when Abiathar is expelled (1 Kings 2:26-27) and Zadok's line established exclusively. The typological significance is that David's reign cannot yet achieve the perfect singular priesthood; it requires two priestly lines in uneasy coexistence. The coming Son of David will hold both king and priest in one person (Ps 110:1-4; Zech 6:12-13; Heb 7:1-17), dissolving the separation between throne and altar that the law maintained. Christ is the Melchizedek-king-priest who ends the Levitical tension.</p>",
    "18": "<p>David's sons are priests (<em>kōhănîm</em>) — a remarkable statement that has no parallel in the Mosaic law and that later scribal tradition softened to 'chief officials' (1 Chron 18:17). David's sons functioning as priests indicates either royal sacral prerogatives or a deliberate typological foreshadowing: the Davidic dynasty moves toward the merger of royalty and priesthood that culminates in Christ, the royal priest after the order of Melchizedek (Ps 110:4; Heb 5:6). If even David's sons bear priestly honor, how much more the greater Son of David who is simultaneously the High Priest who enters once into the holy of holies (Heb 9:12) and the eternal King on David's throne (Luke 1:32-33).</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>David's opening question — 'Is there still anyone left of the house of Saul that I may show him kindness (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) for Jonathan's sake?' — frames the entire chapter as an act of covenant faithfulness. <em>Ḥeseḏ</em> is the great covenant-love word of the OT, the loyalty that goes beyond what duty strictly requires. David acts not because Mephibosheth deserves restoration but because of his covenant with Jonathan (1 Sam 18:3; 20:15-17; 23:18). The type is unmistakable: God's grace to the sinner is not grounded in the sinner's merit but in his covenant with the Son — 'for Jesus' sake.' The question 'Is there still anyone?' echoes the seeking Shepherd (Luke 15:4) and the gracious Father watching for the prodigal (Luke 15:20).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ziba, a servant of Saul's house, is summoned — a man who has survived the transition of power by serving whoever holds it. David learns from Ziba that Jonathan's son remains, establishing the investigative pattern of grace: the king seeks out the object of covenant-kindness before that person can seek him. The antitype is the divine initiative in salvation: God does not wait for sinners to find him but seeks them (Luke 19:10; John 6:44; Rom 5:8). Ziba's role as intermediary who brings information about the hidden beneficiary also typifies the witness function — like John the Baptist announcing the lost sheep that the Shepherd will find.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David repeats his covenant-question with an added qualifier: 'that I may show him the kindness of God (<em>ḥeseḏ ʾĕlōhîm</em>).' The phrase escalates the covenant-love to divine proportion — this is not merely political courtesy but godlike mercy. The addition of <em>ʾĕlōhîm</em> points the typology explicitly upward: David's act toward Mephibosheth is a parable of what God does toward sinners. Paul uses the exact same logic in Rom 5:6-8 — while we were still helpless, God demonstrated his love; and in Eph 2:1-9 the spiritually 'crippled' are raised to sit at the King's table (Eph 2:6) not by their own merit but by the grace of the covenant.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Mephibosheth is identified as being at the house of Machir the son of Ammiel in Lo-debar. <em>Lō-dĕḇār</em> means 'no pasture' or 'nothing' — a place of deprivation, the condition of a refugee from a fallen dynasty hiding in obscurity. The place-name functions typologically: the sinner before grace is in the land of nothing, without pasture, without belonging. Amos 6:13 uses Lo-debar as an ironic reference (Israel taking 'nothing' as a military trophy), deepening the spiritual resonance. David's messengers going to Lo-debar enacts what the gospel does — it enters the land of spiritual nothingness and calls out the one who has no claim to the king's attention.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David sends and fetches Mephibosheth from Lo-debar — the king's initiative traversing the distance between the palace and the refugee's hiding place. The verb <em>wayyišlaḥ</em> (he sent) and <em>wayyiqqāḥēhû</em> (he took/brought him) are the two movements of grace: the sending of the invitation and the drawing of the person to the king. In John's Gospel the same two movements characterize the Incarnation: 'God so loved the world that he gave (<em>sent</em>) his Son' (John 3:16) and 'No one comes to me unless the Father who sent me draws him' (John 6:44). Mephibosheth does not travel to David; David's messengers come to him. Grace is prevenient — it goes before.</p>",
    "6": "<p>When Mephibosheth comes before David, he falls on his face in obeisance and calls himself David's servant. His prostration and self-deprecation before the king ('your servant') mirror the posture of every sinner encountering sovereign grace — undone by undeserved favor, offering nothing but submission. The parallelism with the prodigal son's confession (Luke 15:21, 'I am no longer worthy to be called your son; make me as one of your hired servants') is precise: both Mephibosheth and the prodigal expect rejection and receive restoration. The reversal is grace's signature: the one who prostrates himself is lifted up (Matt 23:12; Luke 14:11).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Mephibosheth calls himself a 'dead dog' (<em>keleb mēt</em>) — the lowest self-designation in the OT idiom, a creature without standing, without value, without claim. The phrase echoes his grandfather Saul's self-deprecation to David (1 Sam 24:14) but in a context of pure helplessness rather than false humility: Mephibosheth genuinely has nothing to offer. The phrase activates the Psalm 22 register where the sufferer is surrounded by dogs (Ps 22:16) and the greater Son of David is treated as a dead dog by his enemies. But here the logic reverses: the dead dog is not abandoned but adopted. Christ, who in his passion was treated as a dead dog (Isa 53:3), raises the spiritually dead to life (John 11:25-26).</p>",
    "9": "<p>David calls Ziba and transfers to Mephibosheth all the land of Saul and his house — a massive economic restoration of the inheritance Mephibosheth had lost. This is not merely welfare but full covenant reinstatement: the land is Mephibosheth's by right of Jonathan's covenant, now formally restored by royal decree. The legal structure typifies justification: not an improvement of status but a full declaratory restoration of what was lost by the covenant representative. Adam lost the inheritance; the Second Adam (Christ) restores it to all who are in him by faith (Rom 5:17-19; Eph 1:11). The very land Saul had held against David is now the gift David gives to Saul's heir.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ziba, his fifteen sons and twenty servants are commanded to farm the land for Mephibosheth, providing the covenant-beneficiary with the means to live without labor in the land. The abundance of provision — fifteen sons and twenty servants mobilized for one man — illustrates the overflowing surplus of grace. This excess points toward the Messianic promise of Amos 9:13-14 (wine dripping from the mountains, plowman overtaking the reaper) and the abundance of the new creation where there will be no poverty or scarcity. Mephibosheth is set up as a permanent beneficiary of covenant kindness: <em>ḥeseḏ</em> does not give once but establishes an ongoing structure of care.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ziba acknowledges the king's command, and the narrator adds the programmatic summary: Mephibosheth shall eat at David's table like one of the king's sons. 'Like one of the king's sons' is the Johannine 'children of God' language (John 1:12): the adopted stranger eats with the family as if born to it. In the NT this reality is described as adoption (<em>huiothesia</em>, Rom 8:15; Eph 1:5) — the Spirit of sonship who cries 'Abba, Father' makes the formerly alien sinner a co-heir with Christ (Rom 8:17). Mephibosheth did not become a son of David in fact; he ate as one by covenant grace. Believers are not sons of God by nature but are constituted sons by the Spirit through faith in the Son.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Mephibosheth has a young son named Mika — the covenant-kindness to Jonathan extends to a third generation, establishing a dynasty of grace that continues after Mephibosheth. This multi-generational reach of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> corresponds to the covenant promise that extends 'to a thousand generations of those who love me and keep my commandments' (Deut 7:9; Exod 20:6). Grace is not a momentary provision but a living covenant that propagates through time. Christologically, the Son of David's grace similarly creates a new family that extends to every generation and nation (Ps 22:30-31; Rev 7:9) — those grafted in by faith produce heirs of the covenant who also come to the King's table.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>The narrative opens with temporal precision: 'In the spring of the year, the time when kings go out to battle.' David stays in Jerusalem while Joab leads the army — the narrator's first indictment. The Davidic king is called to lead his people, not delegate their danger while remaining at leisure. The contrast with Jesus is immediate: Christ does not remain at divine comfort while his people face spiritual warfare but enters the battle himself (Heb 2:14-15; John 12:27), and the greater David does not stay behind at the palace but leads the charge (Rev 19:11). David's withdrawal from the field is the first step toward adultery and murder — confirming that spiritual idleness precedes moral catastrophe.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David rises from his bed in the late afternoon — already a temporal irregularity suggesting a disordered life — and walks on the palace roof where he sees a woman bathing. The roof-walk is privilege used for self-indulgence rather than watchman's duty (cf. Isa 62:6). The verb <em>wayyarʾ</em> (he saw) is morally laden in the OT — the same verb as in Gen 3:6 ('when the woman saw that the tree was good') and Gen 6:2 ('the sons of God saw the daughters of men'). Unchecked seeing leads to wanting; wanting to taking. This verse enacts Jesus's warning in Matt 5:28: 'everyone who looks at a woman with lustful intent has already committed adultery with her in his heart.' David at his worst is the anti-type against which Christ's perfect obedience stands.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David sends messengers, takes Bathsheba, lies with her, and she conceives — four swift verbs enacting the descent from covetousness to adultery. The grammar resists lingering: the act is narrated with brutal economy, and the narrator adds 'for she had purified herself from her uncleanness' to make clear that she was ritually clean and therefore the conception is David's, not her husband's. David uses his royal power to violate a covenant-law that he himself was meant to embody (Deut 17:17, 'he shall not acquire many wives'). The king as predator inverts the covenant order; the true King, by contrast, lays down his life for his Bride rather than taking from her (Eph 5:25). David's sin here generates the entire crisis of Nathan's parable (ch12), where David = rich man, Uriah = poor man, Bathsheba = the single ewe lamb.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Bathsheba sends word: 'I am pregnant.' The brief message is the pivot of the narrative — David's private sin now has a public consequence he must manage. This is the moment when concealment replaces repentance, and a chain of deceptions and violence begins. The contrast with the Annunciation (Luke 1:31) is instructive: both are messages about a miraculous conception, but Bathsheba's pregnancy signals guilt and sets in motion a cover-up, while Mary's pregnancy signals grace and unfolds into redemption. The pregnancy that must be hidden is the antitype; the pregnancy that is proclaimed to the world is the fulfillment. David's response to the news is manipulation; God's response to human sin is Incarnation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>David sends to Joab to bring Uriah home from the battlefield — the king's first attempt at cover-up, using military logistics to arrange a conjugal visit that would make the pregnancy plausibly Uriah's. The irony deepens as the narrative proceeds: Uriah will prove more righteous than David in every exchange. David, the covenant-keeper who danced before the ark (ch6), now attempts to manipulate one of his most loyal servants into unwitting complicity in deception. Uriah's integrity will inadvertently expose David's corruption. The type-pattern anticipates the gospel: the righteous man (Uriah) is ultimately destroyed to cover the powerful man's sin — a preview of the legal mechanism of Christ's passion where the innocent dies for the guilty, though in the gospel the innocent dies voluntarily.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Uriah arrives and David asks about the welfare of Joab, the army, and the war — a facade of royal pastoral concern that masks the actual agenda. The irony intensifies because Uriah's report about his comrades is the very service David has abdicated (v1). Uriah is fighting; David should be fighting. Uriah cares about the welfare of the troops; David is using his troops as pawns. This inversion of covenantal roles recapitulates the Adam-Christ contrast: Adam, charged to guard the garden, abdicated to the serpent's agenda; Christ, the new Adam, guards his flock at the cost of his own life (John 10:11). David in ch11 is Adam in the garden — the appointed guardian who becomes the transgressor.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David tells Uriah to go home and wash his feet — a euphemism (and perhaps a literal invitation to enjoy marital relations after the fatigue of the march). David sends a present after him, a generous royal gift that is actually bait in a trap. The gift of food and hospitality designed to deceive echoes the corrupted hospitality motif running through the OT (Gen 26:10; Judg 19) — covenant hospitality turned predatory. Uriah's response in v9 makes David's gift irrelevant: Uriah refuses to go home. The loyal soldier's refusal of the king's 'gift' actually exposes the gift as manipulation, a pattern repeated in the wilderness temptation where Satan offers Jesus what is already his by right (Matt 4:8-9).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Uriah sleeps at the door of the king's house with all the servants of his lord, refusing to go home to his wife. The verb <em>wayyiškāḇ</em> — he slept — is the same root as David's sin (wayyiškāḇ ʿimmāh, 'he lay with her,' v4), but here it is entirely innocent: Uriah lies down at the gate in solidarity with the soldiers who have no home to go to. The contrast is precise: David's bed is the site of sin; Uriah's sleeping place is the site of covenant loyalty. The Hittite soldier embodies the covenant ethos of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> that David has abandoned. This moral inversion — the Gentile more faithful than the Israelite king — runs from Rahab and Ruth to the Centurion of Matt 8:10 and Cornelius of Acts 10.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David learns that Uriah did not go home — his cover-up plan has failed. He summons Uriah to interrogate him. The king cross-examines his own victim, a grotesque parody of the judicial role that the king was meant to embody (Prov 16:10). David is simultaneously judge and criminal, the very corruption that Ps 82 indicts ('How long will you judge unjustly?'). The true David, by contrast, is the judge who himself undergoes judgment for his people (Isa 53:8; 2 Cor 5:21) — he does not exploit the asymmetry of power but inverts it, accepting condemnation on behalf of those he should condemn. David's interrogation of Uriah is one of Scripture's most searing portraits of power's corruption.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Uriah's speech is the moral center of ch11: 'The ark and Israel and Judah dwell in tents, and my lord Joab and the servants of my lord are camping in the open field. Shall I then go to my house to eat and to drink and to lie with my wife? As you live and as your soul lives, I will not do this thing.' Uriah's oath is by David's life — the king he is about to shame by contrast. The theological key is <em>the ark</em>: Uriah will not enjoy domestic comfort while the ark (YHWH's covenant presence) is in a tent. The soldier's theology of solidarity with YHWH's cause exceeds his king's. The antitype is Christ's kenosis (Phil 2:6-7) — the Son does not cling to the comfort of heaven while his people languish; he empties himself and camps in the flesh.</p>",
    "12": "<p>David asks Uriah to stay another day and he will send him back — buying time for a second strategy (the drinking party of v13) after the first cover-up failed. Each additional day of delay accumulates moral debt: David continues to use Uriah without telling him the truth, treating this loyal soldier as an instrument rather than a person. The instrumental use of persons violates the <em>imago Dei</em> principle that every human being is made in God's image and is not reducible to a tool (Gen 1:27; Jas 3:9). The contrast with Christ's treatment of his followers is absolute: Jesus lays down his life for his servants (John 15:13), turning the master-servant hierarchy upside down (Mark 10:45).</p>",
    "13": "<p>David gets Uriah drunk — a final attempt to overcome his conscience through wine. Even intoxicated, Uriah does not go home but sleeps again among the servants. Uriah's integrity survives impairment: even his unconscious impulses are faithful. The typological force of Uriah's consistent refusal across all three strategies (invitation, gift, wine) is that no external pressure can corrupt a man of genuine covenant loyalty. This is the exact obedience that Adam failed in the garden (temptation overcame him) and that Christ demonstrated in Gethsemane — not my will but yours (Luke 22:42). Uriah is a foil who reveals by contrast what covenant faithfulness actually looks like under pressure.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David writes a letter to Joab and sends it by Uriah's own hand — the most cynical detail in the narrative. Uriah carries his own death sentence without knowing it, trusting the king whose trust he has earned. This is the moment that transforms adultery into a premeditated murder conspiracy. The sealed letter is a close parallel to the written death-order against Uriah that Bathsheba later reads with horror. The image of the innocent man delivering his own death warrant appears in Apocryphal traditions and typologically adumbrates the Passion: the innocent Christ is handed over by his own people ('he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him,' John 1:11), and his own disciples carry the betrayal money (Matt 26:14-15).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The letter's content is explicit: 'Set Uriah in the forefront of the hardest fighting, and then draw back from him, that he may be struck down and die.' This is premeditated judicial murder using military means — an assassination disguised as battlefield mishap. David's command to Joab makes Joab a partner in the crime, implicating the entire command structure of the army. The command reveals the full depth of David's corruption: the king who was meant to execute justice is executing injustice against the most loyal of his servants. The antitype is not merely the contrast with Christ's innocence but the specific mechanism of the Passion: the authorities who put Jesus to death also used official structures to accomplish what was actually murder (John 19:12-16; Acts 2:23).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Joab follows the order, placing Uriah at the position where he knows the defenders are strongest. Joab's compliance reveals that the king's moral failure has corrupted his commander. One man's sin descends through the chain of command, implicating subordinates in guilt they might not have chosen freely. The systemic spread of David's sin anticipates Paul's analysis of Adam's sin: 'by the one man's disobedience the many were made sinners' (Rom 5:19). The commander who once fought YHWH's wars faithfully now engineers the death of an innocent man at the king's behest. Sin in leadership is not contained — it flows downward and outward through all who serve the compromised leader.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The men of the city (Ammonite defenders) come out and fight Joab's forces — Uriah the Hittite is among those who fall in the battle. The death itself is embedded in the larger casualty report that Joab will send, making it appear incidental. This is the mechanism David designed: collective military failure masking targeted assassination. The theological weight is that YHWH allows this moment of successful wickedness — David achieves his immediate goal — because the full judgment will come through Nathan (ch12). The apparent success of evil is a consistent OT pattern (Lam 3:37-38) that prepares for the cross: the crucifixion appears to be the triumph of wickedness, but it is the most paradoxical act of redemptive justice in all of history (Acts 2:23; 1 Cor 2:8).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Joab sends a messenger to David with a full report of the battle — embedding the news of Uriah's death within a larger account of military operations, as David requested. The report strategy reveals the conspiracy's sophistication: David wanted deniability, a death that looked like war. But the narrator and the reader know the truth, and more importantly, YHWH knows (v27: 'the thing that David had done displeased YHWH'). The hidden knowledge of God that watches human concealment is a theme throughout Scripture (Gen 16:13; Ps 44:21; Heb 4:13), and it grounds the doctrine of divine judgment: nothing is hidden that will not be revealed (Luke 12:2-3), and the Judge of all the earth will do right (Gen 18:25).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Joab prepares the messenger with a hypothetical royal rebuke about approaching the city wall too closely, drawn from the story of Abimelech at Thebez (Judg 9:50-54). Joab uses a historical example of military folly as rhetorical inoculation — anticipating David's anger and defusing it before the name 'Uriah' is mentioned. The intertextual reference to Abimelech is ironic: Abimelech was killed by a woman's millstone in an illegitimate siege — a death that Scripture records as divine judgment. Joab reaches for a cautionary tale of military hubris and its consequences, not realizing that the Uriah situation is itself subject to divine judgment far exceeding the rebuke David might give for tactical recklessness.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Joab instructs the messenger: if the king becomes angry about the approach to the city wall, remind him of Abimelech. The conversation that Joab scripts for the messenger is a rehearsal of how to deflect royal anger through historical analogy — sophisticated court politics in the service of murder concealment. The court culture capable of such maneuvering is the product of accumulated compromise: no one around David corrects him at this moment; everyone is complicit in managing consequences rather than confronting sin. The absence of a prophetic voice in ch11 (Nathan does not appear until ch12) parallels the silence before the storm — judgment is gathering while the court busies itself with administrative crisis management.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The reference to Abimelech's death by a woman's millstone at Thebez (Judg 9:50-54) serves Joab's rhetorical strategy, but its echo in this context is charged: Abimelech died as a consequence of his violent and illegitimate reign, struck down by a woman he had terrorized. David is about to receive a similar judgment by a different means — through Nathan's prophetic parable in ch12, and through the sword that 'will never depart from your house' (12:10). The OT habit of recycling historical cautionary tales into new contexts reveals how biblical narrative accumulates moral weight: each new act of violence or injustice is judged against the accumulated record of how God has dealt with similar acts before.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The messenger travels and comes to David and gives him the full report — the mechanics of communication across the narrative underline the normalcy within which evil is being transacted. No supernatural darkness descends; the sun continues to shine; messengers travel normally. The banality of the evil in ch11 — war continues, messages are sent, plans are implemented — prefigures Hannah Arendt's observation that great evil operates through ordinary bureaucratic processes. The prophet will call it out in ch12, but until then the machinery of court life masks the magnitude of what has been done. The plain recitation of events is itself the narrator's indictment: everything is proceeding normally, and everything is catastrophically wrong.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The messenger reports the battle's course — the Ammonites prevailed in the open field, the Israelites were driven back toward the gate, but the archers shot from the wall. The tactical detail establishes that Joab's army paid a real price beyond Uriah to accomplish the king's cover-up: other Israelite soldiers died in the artificially exposed position. David's sin has cost innocent lives beyond Uriah's. The cost of sin in Scripture is never confined to the guilty party — it spreads to the innocent who are caught in its wake. This dynamic reaches its theological apex in Christ who, though himself innocent, absorbs the cost of human sin that has spread to all of creation (Rom 8:19-22).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The messenger concludes by naming Uriah the Hittite among those who died — a subordinate clause embedded in the casualty report, as Joab had designed. The matter-of-fact delivery of Uriah's death, sandwiched between military statistics, is the final touch of David's conspiracy. The king has achieved what he wanted: Uriah is dead, and it looks like war. But the narrative has positioned the reader to know the truth; and YHWH, who sees through every human device (Prov 15:3; Ps 139:1-4), sees through this one. The concealed murder will be exposed by a shepherd parable from a prophet — the Word of God penetrating the court's conspiracy with a story about a lamb (12:1-4).</p>",
    "25": "<p>David's message back to Joab — 'Do not let this trouble you; the sword devours now this one and now that one' — is a cynical reduction of Uriah's targeted murder to the randomness of battlefield death. The platitude 'the sword devours one or another' is not false as a general statement, but as David's response to the news of the man he ordered killed, it is a lie. David consoles Joab for doing what David commanded him to do, confirming that the cover-up is now a shared secret between them. The moral distance David is placing between himself and the act ('the sword devours') is precisely the kind of language that prophetic confrontation must pierce — Nathan in ch12 will remove every layer of abstraction and say simply: 'You are the man' (12:7).</p>",
    "26": "<p>When Bathsheba hears that Uriah her husband is dead, she mourns for him — the Hebrew text specifies that she 'lamented' (<em>wattispoḏ</em>) her husband, the formal mourning rite. The brief notice of her grief is the narrator's humanizing of Bathsheba: she is not a passive object but a wife who has lost her husband to the machinations of a king who should have protected him. The lamentation also marks time — the period of mourning must pass before the next step in David's cover-up can proceed. The rhythm of death and mourning and then David's swift action to take her reveals David's impatience: he cannot even allow the full mourning period before making Bathsheba part of the cover-up by marriage.</p>",
    "27": "<p>When the mourning was over, David sent and brought Bathsheba to his house; she became his wife and bore him a son. The narrative then adds the theological verdict: 'But the thing that David had done displeased YHWH.' The final sentence is the entire theological weight of the chapter — everything that seemed to go according to plan, every cover-up that apparently succeeded, is undone by four Hebrew words: <em>wayyēraʿ bĕʿênê YHWH</em> — 'it was evil in the eyes of YHWH.' The divine commentary lands after the human story has apparently resolved itself: David has what he wanted, Uriah is dead, Bathsheba is queen, the child is on the way. But YHWH's evaluation reframes everything. The typological contrast with Christ is total: David achieves his will against God's; Christ achieves God's will against his own comfort (Luke 22:42).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('2samuel', 'christ')
    merge_comm(c, FILL)
    save_comm('2samuel', 'christ', c)

    import json as _json
    inter = _json.load(open(ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / '2samuel.json'))
    for ch in sorted(inter.keys(), key=int):
        total = len(inter[ch])
        have = len(c.get(str(ch), {}))
        status = 'complete' if have == total else f'partial {have}/{total}'
        if status != 'complete':
            print(f'  ch {ch}: {status} ({total} verses)')
    total_inter = sum(len(v) for v in inter.values())
    total_have = sum(len(v) for v in c.values())
    print(f'  Overall 2samuel/christ: {total_have}/{total_inter}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
